-{"id":"br-r37-c1-00zcu","title":"testing(metamorphic): MST algorithm equivalence (boruvka == kruskal == prim total weight)","description":"Metamorphic property: for any connected weighted undirected graph, the total edge weight of the minimum spanning tree must be identical regardless of which algorithm computes it (boruvka, kruskal, prim). Add tests/python/test_mst_algorithm_equivalence.py exercising the three new MST edge iterators (boruvka_mst_edges, kruskal_mst_edges, prim_mst_edges from br-wjv9o) on a parameterized matrix of random graphs (seeded gnp_random_graph at varying n/p, plus path_graph, cycle_graph, complete_graph, balanced_tree). Assert sum of edge weights matches across all 3 algorithms, and equals nx baseline. Catches regressions in any of the iterators silently dropping edges or picking suboptimal ones.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-26T04:06:46.256697345Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T04:12:42.391651771Z","close_reason":"Landed tests/python/test_mst_algorithm_equivalence.py (commit c1b0d87) with 28 metamorphic tests covering: (1) three-algorithm total-weight agreement on 8 fixtures, (2) nx baseline cross-check, (3) spanning-tree property (acyclic, n-1 edges, all nodes covered), (4) spanning-forest on disconnected graph (n-c edges where c = component count), (5) uniform-weight sanity (K_n total = n-1). Catches regressions where any iterator drops edges or picks suboptimal ones.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
+{"id":"br-r37-c1-00zcu","title":"testing(metamorphic): MST algorithm equivalence (boruvka == kruskal == prim total weight)","description":"Metamorphic property: for any connected weighted undirected graph, the total edge weight of the minimum spanning tree must be identical regardless of which algorithm computes it (boruvka, kruskal, prim). Add tests/python/test_mst_algorithm_equivalence.py exercising the three new MST edge iterators (boruvka_mst_edges, kruskal_mst_edges, prim_mst_edges from br-wjv9o) on a parameterized matrix of random graphs (seeded gnp_random_graph at varying n/p, plus path_graph, cycle_graph, complete_graph, balanced_tree). Assert sum of edge weights matches across all 3 algorithms, and equals nx baseline. Catches regressions in any of the iterators silently dropping edges or picking suboptimal ones.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-26T04:06:46.256697345Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-26T04:18:41.877348816Z","closed_at":"2026-04-26T04:18:41.875470378Z","close_reason":"Already shipped by another agent: tests/python/test_mst_algorithm_equivalence.py exists with 28 metamorphic test cases (boruvka == kruskal == prim total weight on gnp/path/cycle/K_n/binary_tree fixtures, plus disconnected, tie-breaking, and finite-weight sanity sub-cases) and they all pass. No additional work needed — the metamorphic property is locked in.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-01","title":"REVIEW: [HIGH] condensation used wrong SCC labeling (source-first instead of sink-first)","description":"fnx.condensation(G) labeled SCCs via the Rust _condensation_raw internal order, which numbered source SCCs first. nx numbers SCCs in strongly_connected_components() order (sinks first). Consequence: C.graph['mapping'], C.nodes[i]['members'], and condensation edges had integer labels flipped relative to networkx, silently breaking downstream code that indexes SCCs by label. Fixed by rebuilding condensation on top of fnx's own strongly_connected_components iterator so labels stay bit-compatible.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed: condensation now iterates strongly_connected_components(G) and assigns indices in emission order, matching networkx's convention. Tested on 5-node 2-SCC DAG; mapping, edges, and members all match nx exactly; scc= arg path and empty-graph path also match.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-02","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] node_connectivity on MultiGraph with parallel edges returned simple-graph value","description":"fnx.node_connectivity(MultiGraph) called into _raw_node_connectivity which collapses parallel edges. On e.g. K3 with extra parallel edges between two pairs, networkx returns min-degree=3 (parallel edges inflate the degree bound) while fnx returned 2 (simple-graph κ=n−1). Fixed by delegating multigraph inputs to networkx to preserve parity. Simple Graph/DiGraph continue to use the Rust fast path.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed: node_connectivity now delegates when G.is_multigraph(). Verified on K3-parallel, K3 MG no-parallel, MDG with parallel edges — all match nx.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
 {"id":"br-r37-c1-03","title":"REVIEW: [MEDIUM] edge_connectivity returned float and ignored MultiGraph parallel edges","description":"Two related defects in edge_connectivity: (1) simple Graph path returned a float (e.g. 2.0) via the max-flow pipeline while nx returns an int cardinality (2). (2) MultiGraph path collapsed parallel edges: on K3 with extra parallel edges fnx returned 2.0 vs nx's 3. Fixed by coercing int-valued floats to int before returning, and delegating multigraph inputs to networkx.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","created_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","updated_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","closed_at":"2026-04-24T00:00:00Z","close_reason":"Fixed: MG/MDG delegate to nx; simple Graph path casts integral float back to int. Verified across K3 simple, DG, MG with/without parallel, MDG — all match nx in value and type.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0}
